According to western press reports, Iranian voters have a limited choice in the Presidential election, 2021. Ayatollah Ali Khamenei has manipulated a like-minded hardliner will become the new president. The one reformist candidate, Mohsen Mehralizadeh and a hardliner, Alireza Zakani dropped out leaving five candidates in the field, which is familiar ploy in Iranian presidential elections to ensure the election of similar individuals. The former governor of the Central Bank of Iran Abdolnasar Hemmati, who is a moderate and a member of the political establishment may have stood an outside chance but, opinion is ‘that Iranians are exhausted form years of corruption, sanctions, economic volatility and grown apathetic to these elections’.

"Mohsen Mehralizadeh, the only reformist candidate approved to participate in this week's Iranian presidential election, has withdrawn from the race leaving former central bank governor Abdolnaser Hemmati as the sole non-conservative on the ballot." https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/2225193-sole-reformist-candidate-drops-out-of-iran-election

Judiciary chief Ebrahim Raisi will now be seen as the clear frontrunner to succeed Hassan Rouhani, a moderate.

Ebrahim Raisi is a hardliner amongst six other inconsequential candidates selected by Iran’s Guardian Council to run for office in the forthcoming Presidential election. Political commentators have been predicting a low turnout due to voter apathy driven by the primary concern of the country’s dire economic situation and a scepticism that their votes will make any difference. The opinion in Iran is that a low voter turnout (less than 50%) gives advantage to the Conservatives. A high turnout would benefit the reformist camp and have therefore been excluded from the list of those allowed to run for President.
All withdrawals after registration endorsed Raisi. Has name recognition from the previous election as a challenger to Rouhani.
The Council of Guardians has eliminated all of the other serious candidates, clearing the way for Raisi.[1]
